WEBVTT

00:07.094 --> 00:08.878
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
Previously on...</i>

00:08.921 --> 00:10.097
- "Dateline" is here?
- Wow.

00:10.140 --> 00:12.490
Will you dig up
something on Pam Hupp?

00:12.534 --> 00:13.926
There's no direct
evidence here

00:13.970 --> 00:15.015
that connects her to the crime.

00:15.058 --> 00:16.103
Well, it looks like
we're facing

00:16.146 --> 00:18.018
a home court advantage
here, Russ.

00:18.061 --> 00:19.628
Did you guys
ever find that letter

00:19.671 --> 00:22.500
about Russ putting a pillow
over her face?

00:22.544 --> 00:25.329
Luminol photos were taken.
We found blood in the kitchen.

00:25.373 --> 00:27.984
We the jury
find Russell Faria

00:28.028 --> 00:29.681
guilty of murder
in the first degree.

00:29.725 --> 00:31.161
I'm not gonna quit
until he's free.

00:31.205 --> 00:32.293
I set up a trust

00:32.336 --> 00:34.077
for the daughters
of Betsy Faria.

00:34.121 --> 00:35.905
I'd like to transfer
the balance

00:35.948 --> 00:37.994
to my personal checking.

00:40.431 --> 00:42.172
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
No one knows a mother</i>

00:42.216 --> 00:44.131
<i>like her daughter.</i>

00:44.174 --> 00:46.046
Go ahead, Grandma,
make a wish.

00:46.089 --> 00:50.528
<i>♪</i>

00:50.572 --> 00:52.443
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
A very, shall we say,</i>

00:52.487 --> 00:55.229
<i>special relationship.</i>

00:55.272 --> 00:59.711
<i>♪</i>

00:59.755 --> 01:01.191
- Yay.
- Yay!

01:01.235 --> 01:03.106
<i>♪</i>

01:03.150 --> 01:04.847
Gotta get you back
to Autumndale.

01:04.890 --> 01:07.023
Already late meeting
the plumber at our flip.

01:07.067 --> 01:08.546
Oh, I can take Grandma back.

01:08.590 --> 01:11.375
I don't want to go with you.

01:11.419 --> 01:13.725
It's fine.
I'll take her.

01:13.769 --> 01:17.338
Your mom's just protecting
her spot in my will.

01:17.381 --> 01:19.688
<i>narrator: When does money</i> <i>
become an obsession?</i>

01:21.255 --> 01:24.301
<i>By 1977,</i> <i>
Pam had grown up poor,</i>

01:24.345 --> 01:26.216
<i>but she was popular.</i>

01:26.260 --> 01:29.089
<i>She was on the pom-pom squad.</i>

01:29.132 --> 01:30.220
So, Pam,

01:30.264 --> 01:32.092
you gonna give it up
to Randy tonight?

01:32.135 --> 01:33.528
I'm saving myself.

01:33.571 --> 01:36.792
Randy's gotta wait
till after I go to Mizzou,

01:36.835 --> 01:39.229
get my teaching degree.

01:39.273 --> 01:42.102
Man, if he doesn't look good
in that suit.

01:42.145 --> 01:44.800
<i>♪</i>

01:44.843 --> 01:46.932
Aren't you supposed
to stay inside,

01:46.976 --> 01:48.020
with the other teachers?

01:48.064 --> 01:49.152
That Gunderson boy

01:49.196 --> 01:51.241
better have you home
by 11:00, Pam,

01:51.285 --> 01:53.025
and no fooling around.

01:53.069 --> 01:54.375
Don't worry, Mrs. Neumann.

01:54.418 --> 01:56.420
Pam was just saying
she's waiting till marriage.

01:56.464 --> 01:58.422
After Mizzou.

01:58.466 --> 02:01.599
Pam doesn't got the brains
for Mizzou.

02:01.643 --> 02:04.950
And I'm not so sure she has
anything left to save, honey.

02:04.994 --> 02:08.258
This one is very sneaky.

02:08.302 --> 02:09.433
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
Was Pam born</i>

02:09.477 --> 02:11.043
<i>with a certain nature?</i>

02:11.087 --> 02:13.742
<i>He brain wired a certain way?</i>

02:13.785 --> 02:15.526
<i>♪</i>

02:15.570 --> 02:17.354
Don't you walk away from me.

02:17.398 --> 02:19.791
Why don't you have
another drink, Mom?

02:19.835 --> 02:22.011
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
And if biology loaded the gun,</i>

02:22.054 --> 02:23.143
<i>so to speak,</i>

02:23.186 --> 02:25.275
<i>did upbringing fire it?</i>

02:25.319 --> 02:29.627
I will cut you out
of my will, Pam.

02:29.671 --> 02:32.848
<i>♪ And I know that it must be</i> <i>
the woman in you ♪</i>

02:32.891 --> 02:38.375
<i>♪ That brings out</i> <i>
the man in me ♪</i>

02:38.419 --> 02:42.466
<i>♪ Feels like the first time</i>

02:42.510 --> 02:45.904
<i>♪ It feels like</i> <i>
the very first time ♪</i>

02:45.948 --> 02:50.779
<i>♪ And it feels like</i> <i>
the first time ♪</i>

03:00.354 --> 03:02.356
Did you wet yourself?

03:05.881 --> 03:09.537
What did I tell you last time?
Hmm?

03:12.235 --> 03:13.932
Mm.

03:20.374 --> 03:22.245
You're done.

03:22.289 --> 03:24.421
Hm.

03:25.727 --> 03:27.468
And if you even try
to take those off,

03:27.511 --> 03:30.514
it'll be worse for you,
trust me.

03:30.558 --> 03:35.040
I should be the one crying.

03:35.084 --> 03:38.957
You owe me, little girl.

03:39.001 --> 03:42.570
But you got any money?

03:42.613 --> 03:44.049
No.

03:44.093 --> 03:45.964
You're broke.

03:47.488 --> 03:50.099
Rand, we're out of milk.

03:50.142 --> 03:52.362
I need some grocery money.

03:52.406 --> 03:57.367
I'm watching the game.

03:57.411 --> 03:59.500
Come on.

03:59.543 --> 04:01.763
Little late, isn't it, Pam?

04:01.806 --> 04:03.678
I'll go with you.

04:03.721 --> 04:05.114
Mom.

04:05.157 --> 04:06.376
Mom, you're tired.

04:06.420 --> 04:09.553
You want me to bring you
back some gin, yeah?

04:09.597 --> 04:12.904
- Okay, all right.
- All right.

04:12.948 --> 04:15.211
Mm-hmm.

04:16.952 --> 04:18.214
Rand.
- Hmm?

04:18.258 --> 04:20.347
Money.

04:22.566 --> 04:24.829
Thanks for getting milk.

04:24.873 --> 04:27.354
You are a good mom.

04:27.397 --> 04:29.443
Good moms
don't run out of milk.

04:29.486 --> 04:32.272
You were always out of milk.

04:32.315 --> 04:34.186
You were always
out of everything.

04:34.230 --> 04:36.101
'Cause we were poor, dumbass.

04:36.145 --> 04:38.582
Why are you here
if you're just gonna insult me?

04:38.626 --> 04:41.019
Somebody has to keep
an eye on you,

04:41.063 --> 04:42.369
for Sarah's sake.

04:42.412 --> 04:44.632
Oh.

04:45.459 --> 04:48.418
So does that mean you don't
disown my daughter after all?

04:48.462 --> 04:50.899
No, she's still a bastard.

04:50.942 --> 04:52.944
We got married
before she was born.

04:52.988 --> 04:54.337
Sarah is not a bastard.

04:54.381 --> 04:55.991
She's not my family.

04:56.034 --> 04:58.123
That's for sure.

04:58.167 --> 05:01.083
You're going to get milk
or what?

05:09.657 --> 05:10.440
Or what?

05:13.487 --> 05:15.140
<i>♪</i>

05:15.184 --> 05:16.838
Gin and tonic for you.

05:16.881 --> 05:22.452
<i>♪</i>

05:22.496 --> 05:24.976
Uh, no.
So AAA is the last stop

05:25.020 --> 05:26.543
before the pros.

05:26.587 --> 05:29.329
It's got nothing to do with
the automobile association.

05:29.372 --> 05:32.157
<i>♪</i>

05:32.201 --> 05:33.985
I'm headed to play in Florida.

05:34.029 --> 05:36.597
<i>♪</i>

05:36.640 --> 05:42.472
<i>♪ I'm, I'm truly</i> <i>
a travelin' man ♪</i>

05:42.516 --> 05:46.781
<i>♪ Consider me saved</i>

05:46.824 --> 05:50.306
<i>♪ I'm a 20th century boy</i>

05:50.350 --> 05:53.831
<i>♪ In a 21st century world</i>

05:53.875 --> 05:56.356
<i>♪ Got my big double</i> <i>
space boots on ♪</i>

05:56.399 --> 05:59.315
<i>♪ Now I'm on my way</i>

05:59.359 --> 06:06.409
<i>♪</i>

06:11.588 --> 06:14.286
Another G&T for me.

06:14.330 --> 06:17.202
And a beer for AAA over here.

06:17.246 --> 06:19.944
<i>♪</i>

06:19.988 --> 06:22.643
Hi.

06:26.386 --> 06:29.432
Florida, huh?

06:29.476 --> 06:31.303
That's the plan, yeah.

06:31.347 --> 06:33.305
AAA two to three years,

06:33.349 --> 06:35.830
and off to the big leagues.

06:35.873 --> 06:38.876
I like a guy with a plan.

06:38.920 --> 06:41.052
<i>♪ Another rock and roll</i> <i>
superstar ♪</i>

06:41.096 --> 06:45.013
And Florida's real humid,
right?

06:47.755 --> 06:50.497
My mom hates humidity.
Frazzles her hair.

06:50.540 --> 06:55.502
<i>♪</i>

06:55.545 --> 06:57.417
So when do we leave?

06:57.460 --> 07:00.289
<i>♪</i>

07:06.904 --> 07:10.081
Great form, Mrs. Fitzgerald.

07:19.090 --> 07:23.747
- Hmm?
- Yeah.

07:23.791 --> 07:26.141
Mrs. Fitzgerald baked these
for helping out.

07:26.184 --> 07:27.316
Isn't that nice?

07:27.359 --> 07:29.449
Her gout's spread like crazy.

07:29.492 --> 07:31.799
She doesn't have
any family around.

07:31.842 --> 07:34.149
I'm sure you'll take
good care of her.

07:34.192 --> 07:36.151
Mm-hmm.

07:39.241 --> 07:41.461
Hey, may I have some money
for a beer?

07:41.504 --> 07:43.288
Hmm?
Mm, no.

07:43.332 --> 07:45.465
No more spending today.

07:47.031 --> 07:48.250
Mm-mm.

07:48.293 --> 07:50.687
I am not buying you
another bathing suit.

07:50.731 --> 07:53.211
That one barely fits.

07:53.255 --> 07:54.691
When I was your age,

07:54.735 --> 07:57.433
I had to wear pedal pushers
to the pool.

07:57.477 --> 07:58.956
Know why?

07:59.000 --> 08:01.742
Your grandma beat me
with a belt.

08:01.785 --> 08:03.787
You think I ever
got any cookies?

08:07.182 --> 08:08.792
Hmm.

08:18.367 --> 08:19.716
You and baby Travis don't know

08:19.760 --> 08:23.590
how lucky you are to be mine.

08:23.633 --> 08:26.984
Far, far away
from mean, old Grandma.

08:27.028 --> 08:29.813
<i>♪ Spin me around</i>

08:29.857 --> 08:31.293
Can I come with you
to the house?

08:31.336 --> 08:33.338
Scott and I have been thinking
about flipping, too.

08:33.382 --> 08:35.645
Scott.
What's he know?

08:35.689 --> 08:37.386
He got his real estate license.

08:37.429 --> 08:38.866
Anyone can study up.

08:38.909 --> 08:41.564
It doesn't mean
you got the knack.

08:41.608 --> 08:44.262
Actually, Scott found this
perfect foreclosure on Derby.

08:44.306 --> 08:47.614
You guys don't have
the bankroll for this game,

08:47.657 --> 08:50.355
and I don't want to see you
make a mistake

08:50.399 --> 08:53.054
that I gotta fix.

08:53.097 --> 08:57.754
You owe me 15.72

08:57.798 --> 08:59.800
with the fries.

08:59.843 --> 09:01.802
How come Travis
doesn't have to pay?

09:01.845 --> 09:03.107
I do other things.

09:03.151 --> 09:04.718
He does.

09:04.761 --> 09:07.416
Sarah, your mom is always
gonna make you pay.

09:07.459 --> 09:09.549
Grandma, I'm over here.

09:09.592 --> 09:11.246
When she was just
a little bitch,

09:11.289 --> 09:14.554
Pam stole candy
from a corner store

09:14.597 --> 09:16.556
and hid it under the bed,

09:16.599 --> 09:17.992
and she lied to her dad,

09:18.035 --> 09:19.820
said that I was the one
who stole it.

09:19.863 --> 09:21.604
Who do you think he believed?

09:21.648 --> 09:24.128
And she still steals from me.

09:24.172 --> 09:25.390
<i>♪</i>

09:25.434 --> 09:27.262
Grandma's lying.

09:27.305 --> 09:29.656
Her brain is mush.

09:29.699 --> 09:31.048
Let's do cake.

09:31.092 --> 09:32.833
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
Mothers and daughters,</i>

09:32.876 --> 09:34.748
<i>a bond that can't be severed.</i>

09:38.969 --> 09:40.231
Okay, okay.

09:40.275 --> 09:43.147
Hello?
It's Cathy from "Dateline."

09:48.283 --> 09:49.893
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
It had been almost two years</i>

09:49.937 --> 09:51.503
<i>since Russ' conviction,</i>

09:51.547 --> 09:55.464
<i>and Pam had rested</i> <i>
on her laurels.</i>

10:01.122 --> 10:03.037
Hi.

10:03.080 --> 10:04.386
Sorry to just show up,

10:04.429 --> 10:06.388
but you stopped answering
my texts.

10:06.431 --> 10:09.434
Oh, well, first,
nice to meet ya.

10:09.478 --> 10:11.654
And I told ya,
I'm a private person.

10:11.698 --> 10:14.483
I know. But with Joel
pushing for a retrial,

10:14.526 --> 10:17.051
you should really think about
telling your side of the story.

10:17.094 --> 10:18.966
A retrial--who said that?

10:19.009 --> 10:20.924
- Just what I heard.
- Uh-huh.

10:20.968 --> 10:23.666
Kay. Um, well, have a good one.

10:23.710 --> 10:25.625
You might want to send
a new photo, at least.

10:34.938 --> 10:36.853
Ick.

10:36.897 --> 10:39.551
Ironically, it was Pam
that got the ball rolling.

10:39.595 --> 10:41.771
You mean, I could get out?

10:41.815 --> 10:43.730
That's what we're saying.

10:43.773 --> 10:46.297
Lily and Mariah filed
a civil suit against Pam

10:46.341 --> 10:47.821
for the insurance money.

10:47.864 --> 10:49.561
So I was able to use
some of the material

10:49.605 --> 10:51.128
from Pam's civil deposition

10:51.172 --> 10:53.696
as evidence in support of
a thing called a Mooney motion.

10:53.740 --> 10:56.568
Super longshot.
And it worked.

10:56.612 --> 11:00.311
Now, this motion got us
a hearing before a judge.

11:00.355 --> 11:02.966
And he agreed
to grant you a new trial.

11:03.010 --> 11:05.360
Russ, this is a good thing.

11:05.403 --> 11:08.493
I know. Thanks, but
they're a bunch of cheats.

11:08.537 --> 11:10.582
I've already been in here
three years because of them.

11:10.626 --> 11:12.367
What if they just
tear me down again

11:12.410 --> 11:13.760
and I wind up back here, and--
- No, no, no.

11:13.803 --> 11:15.587
Everything is gonna be
different this time, Russ.

11:15.631 --> 11:18.068
This motion guarantees
that we'll be able to bring in

11:18.112 --> 11:20.462
all the evidence
implicating Pam Hupp.

11:20.505 --> 11:22.246
Now, we'd like to request
a bench trial.

11:22.290 --> 11:24.292
That is, one judge,

11:24.335 --> 11:27.991
not an uninformed group
like we had last time.

11:28.035 --> 11:29.471
- Just a judge?
- Just one judge.

11:29.514 --> 11:31.516
- Is that risky?
- Yeah, it's different.

11:31.560 --> 11:34.215
Normally, we only have to
convince one juror out of 12.

11:34.258 --> 11:35.520
Now, those odds
didn't exactly

11:35.564 --> 11:36.739
work in our favor last time,

11:36.783 --> 11:39.133
but this time,
you'll get a new judge,

11:39.176 --> 11:40.787
a fair one.

11:40.830 --> 11:43.224
That's all we need,
and we can win this thing.

11:43.267 --> 11:46.053
But it's up to you.

11:46.096 --> 11:48.272
We don't want to do anything
without your say-so.

11:51.058 --> 11:53.277
If you think it's better...

11:53.321 --> 11:55.279
<i>♪</i>

11:55.323 --> 11:57.673
Let's go for it.

11:57.717 --> 11:58.848
I trust you.

11:58.892 --> 12:02.983
<i>♪</i>

12:05.028 --> 12:06.813
Mrs. Hupp is--

12:06.856 --> 12:08.553
It's fine. It's fine.

12:08.597 --> 12:10.860
You said it would take
five or six years

12:10.904 --> 12:12.427
for an appeal.

12:12.470 --> 12:16.344
What's this about retrial?
- Uh--

12:16.387 --> 12:18.346
It's the most ridiculous thing.

12:18.389 --> 12:21.001
My ten-year-old
could file something better.

12:21.044 --> 12:22.350
A Mooney motion.

12:22.393 --> 12:24.352
- Money motion?
- Mooney.

12:24.395 --> 12:25.962
I could show you
my bank statement.

12:26.006 --> 12:27.529
- It's Mooney.
- The money's still there.

12:27.572 --> 12:28.704
I'm not the kind of person...
- Right, it's--

12:28.748 --> 12:30.271
Who goes out
and just blows money.

12:30.314 --> 12:31.402
- No, I know.
- Not me. Never has been me.

12:31.446 --> 12:32.534
- Of course.
- I went to college.

12:32.577 --> 12:34.144
You know, top of my class.

12:34.188 --> 12:35.798
I didn't need that money.
- Right.

12:35.842 --> 12:37.539
And if he's
such a great lawyer,

12:37.582 --> 12:39.628
and he charges what he charges,

12:39.671 --> 12:41.848
he's gonna crack
this whole thing open

12:41.891 --> 12:43.066
based on a deposition?

12:43.110 --> 12:44.459
What deposition?

12:44.502 --> 12:48.332
The one for the girls'
lawsuit against you.

12:48.376 --> 12:50.508
Because of what you said.

13:01.911 --> 13:03.957
Are you okay?

13:06.220 --> 13:10.746
I'm fine.

13:10.790 --> 13:13.053
Joel's just using
your testimony

13:13.096 --> 13:19.015
to say that the only reason
that you opened the trust

13:19.059 --> 13:22.410
is because you felt pressured
by the cops or me?

13:22.453 --> 13:26.066
No. That is not true.

13:26.109 --> 13:30.548
That is ridiculousness.

13:30.592 --> 13:34.074
I know it's not--
it's ridiculousness.

13:34.117 --> 13:35.466
So you never said that.

13:35.510 --> 13:40.645
Are you saying that--
that this is my fault?

13:40.689 --> 13:42.082
No.

13:42.125 --> 13:44.258
Not at all.

13:44.301 --> 13:47.000
Just that Schwartz is using--

13:47.043 --> 13:51.439
Schwartz is doing
that one-sided BS.

13:51.482 --> 13:53.484
But we will have to prep,

13:53.528 --> 13:55.530
so I'm gonna have Tina
schedule some time.

13:55.573 --> 13:57.314
Dream team.

13:57.358 --> 13:59.969
Right.

14:04.931 --> 14:07.759
Let me help you with the door.
There you go.

14:07.803 --> 14:09.109
Thanks, Pam.

14:09.152 --> 14:12.286
Bye.

14:12.329 --> 14:15.071
Tina, um,

14:15.115 --> 14:16.594
do you understand Facebook?

14:16.638 --> 14:19.293
Because I made a campaign
account for my reelection,

14:19.336 --> 14:23.514
but am I a page?
Am I a person? What am I?

14:23.558 --> 14:26.213
I don't know, but I was
actually just going over

14:26.256 --> 14:27.605
the original evidence list,

14:27.649 --> 14:29.564
and it seems like there
are a few items on here

14:29.607 --> 14:32.915
that weren't filed correctly
the first time around,

14:32.959 --> 14:35.222
or never even tested.
- Hmm.

14:35.265 --> 14:36.353
Should I test them now?

14:36.397 --> 14:38.138
Yeah. Test everything.

14:38.181 --> 14:40.836
Against Russ and anyone else?

14:40.880 --> 14:43.752
Why would we test against
anyone but Russ?

14:43.795 --> 14:46.711
So we can, I don't know,
be on the right side of things.

14:46.755 --> 14:49.671
We are on the right side.
We won.

14:49.714 --> 14:51.499
Seems like I knew
what I was doing then.

14:51.542 --> 14:53.414
Why would we change
tactics now?

14:53.457 --> 14:57.461
<i>♪</i>

14:57.505 --> 14:58.767
<i>She was just weird.</i>

14:58.810 --> 15:00.769
It was like she was blaming me
or something.

15:00.812 --> 15:03.424
It's not my fault
that Betsy's girls

15:03.467 --> 15:04.729
made me talk to their lawyer.

15:04.773 --> 15:06.818
She's the DA.
It's her job to put Russ away

15:06.862 --> 15:09.473
and keep him there.
Her job.

15:09.517 --> 15:10.910
Hey.

15:10.953 --> 15:14.739
We're behind on the mortgage
and--

15:14.783 --> 15:17.699
That's all that's left
of Betsy's insurance.

15:17.742 --> 15:20.615
And it's--it's sentimental.

15:20.658 --> 15:22.878
She would want me to save it
for a rainy day.

15:22.922 --> 15:24.706
Plus, people are late on bills
all the time.

15:24.749 --> 15:27.143
Nothing ever happens.

15:27.187 --> 15:28.579
We gotta think bigger.

15:28.623 --> 15:30.712
Is now the time for bigger,
though?

15:30.755 --> 15:33.541
It's the time for big swings.

15:33.584 --> 15:35.282
Russ is getting a retrial,

15:35.325 --> 15:36.892
and "Dateline" is up my ass.

15:36.936 --> 15:40.069
Well, reporters are rats. -
Yeah, they are.

15:40.113 --> 15:41.723
You know what my mom
used to do with rats?

15:41.766 --> 15:43.855
She liked that poison
that killed them slow.

15:43.899 --> 15:45.509
I like the kind with zinc.

15:45.553 --> 15:47.033
It makes 'em pop

15:47.076 --> 15:48.121
right from the get-go,

15:48.164 --> 15:50.384
you know?

15:50.427 --> 15:52.908
Well, my mama always said

15:52.952 --> 15:55.476
to make sure
they got nothing to feed on.

15:58.522 --> 16:01.743
<i>♪</i>

16:01.786 --> 16:04.224
You are so right.

16:04.267 --> 16:05.747
Huh.

16:05.790 --> 16:11.361
If Russ never gets out,

16:11.405 --> 16:14.364
there's no story.

16:14.408 --> 16:16.062
No "Dateline."

16:16.105 --> 16:17.541
<i>narrator: No "Dateline."</i>

16:17.585 --> 16:19.630
<i>Hmm. We'll see.</i>

16:22.459 --> 16:24.722
Would you scootch back
a bit for me, please?

16:24.766 --> 16:26.159
We're gonna try
and get a shot of you

16:26.202 --> 16:28.552
through the doorway, like this.

16:28.596 --> 16:29.901
Oh, boy.

16:29.945 --> 16:31.555
There's no need
to be nervous.

16:31.599 --> 16:33.470
We're not here
to interrogate you.

16:33.514 --> 16:35.037
It's okay.

16:35.081 --> 16:37.735
I know what you're here for.

16:37.779 --> 16:39.563
I'm here to report the facts.

16:39.607 --> 16:41.043
You're gonna say
that the facts

16:41.087 --> 16:43.915
don't point to Russ, right?

16:43.959 --> 16:47.049
There are certain facts

16:47.093 --> 16:49.530
that call into question
that theory.

16:49.573 --> 16:51.662
And it's my responsibility
to report those too.

16:51.706 --> 16:55.884
You mean some people saying
it's Pam Hupp?

16:55.927 --> 16:58.843
I know what some folks think,

16:58.887 --> 17:01.759
and I can only guess
what they're saying about me.

17:01.803 --> 17:03.761
But Pam was there

17:03.805 --> 17:06.068
for the family and the police.

17:06.112 --> 17:08.592
She was their star witness.

17:08.636 --> 17:10.855
So how could that be

17:10.899 --> 17:14.772
if she were the guilty one?

17:14.816 --> 17:16.078
<i>Pam, it's great</i>

17:16.122 --> 17:17.819
that you wanted to come back in
and help us,

17:17.862 --> 17:23.129
but a lot of this we know
from the first time around.

17:23.172 --> 17:27.959
Did you know that Betsy
had an inverted nipple?

17:28.003 --> 17:30.092
No, I didn't.

17:31.224 --> 17:33.487
Well, I told her
it was a sign of cancer,

17:33.530 --> 17:36.359
and it sure was.

17:36.403 --> 17:38.187
I mean,

17:38.231 --> 17:42.061
we just spent
a whole lot of time together,

17:42.104 --> 17:43.671
you know?

17:43.714 --> 17:45.325
Um, and I did.

17:45.368 --> 17:51.026
I, uh, replaced
what a husband would be.

17:52.506 --> 17:56.031
So you were filling voids
they had in their marriage.

17:56.075 --> 17:57.163
- Yeah.
- Uh-huh.

17:57.206 --> 17:59.426
And after that,

17:59.469 --> 18:04.692
I knew she had
a mad crush on me.

18:04.735 --> 18:07.825
I didn't know to what level.

18:07.869 --> 18:09.436
It didn't matter.

18:09.479 --> 18:13.092
I think that happens
with people.

18:13.135 --> 18:15.572
But I think
because I always had her back,

18:15.616 --> 18:17.139
she trusted me.

18:17.183 --> 18:20.882
She really, really,

18:20.925 --> 18:23.189
really loved me.

18:23.232 --> 18:28.324
And it just kept growing
from that.

18:28.368 --> 18:31.893
She wanted to be more.

18:31.936 --> 18:34.852
Oh, you mean, like--
like, a sexual relationship?

18:34.896 --> 18:36.158
Yeah.

18:36.202 --> 18:38.204
But I said,
"No, that's not me,"

18:38.247 --> 18:40.249
and all of that,
nd she got sort of mad.

18:40.293 --> 18:42.773
So over time--

18:42.817 --> 18:44.166
it didn't start out that way--

18:44.210 --> 18:48.344
but our relationship
became more.

18:48.388 --> 18:52.218
We were sexual together.

18:52.261 --> 18:53.393
Don't like girls.

18:53.436 --> 18:55.482
Never been attracted to girls.

18:55.525 --> 18:58.615
I'll go watch "Magic Mike XL"
right now.

18:59.877 --> 19:01.401
Love men.

19:01.444 --> 19:05.666
But sex isn't a big deal to me,

19:05.709 --> 19:10.192
so it was something
I sacrificed for her.

19:10.236 --> 19:12.847
Well, it's the caregiver
in you.

19:12.890 --> 19:14.936
Exactly.

19:14.979 --> 19:17.330
And, uh,
never mentioned it before

19:17.373 --> 19:19.723
because it's private,

19:19.767 --> 19:24.772
and, um, she was very serious
about nobody knows,

19:24.815 --> 19:25.903
'cause she was scared
what Russ would do,

19:25.947 --> 19:27.644
but he knew.

19:27.688 --> 19:29.211
He was jealous.

19:29.255 --> 19:31.648
Thought we were ripping
each other's clothes off

19:31.692 --> 19:32.780
all the time.

19:32.823 --> 19:35.261
But it wasn't like that.

19:35.304 --> 19:36.610
We weren't lesbians.

19:36.653 --> 19:39.090
- Mm.
- We just had this

19:39.134 --> 19:41.484
sexual thing between us.

19:41.528 --> 19:42.616
Betsy getting that from you,

19:42.659 --> 19:45.619
that must have made Russ
really mad.

19:45.662 --> 19:47.186
Big time.

19:47.229 --> 19:49.449
Russ and me got physical
over it.

19:49.492 --> 19:51.973
<i>we were in the basement</i> <i>
playing softball</i>

19:52.016 --> 19:53.757
<i>when Russ comes home.</i>

19:53.801 --> 19:57.152
<i>He goes, "What the hell</i> <i>
are you two doing down here?"</i>

20:01.200 --> 20:03.506
<i>"If I ever catch you two...</i>

20:03.550 --> 20:05.987
<i>"muff thumpers together again,</i>

20:06.030 --> 20:07.989
<i>"I'll stab ya</i>

20:08.032 --> 20:10.644
<i>and bury ya out in the yard."</i>

20:10.687 --> 20:13.995
<i>♪</i>

20:14.038 --> 20:15.779
"Muff thumpers?"

20:15.823 --> 20:17.259
That's what he said.

20:18.434 --> 20:21.611
- Huh.
- Okay.

20:21.655 --> 20:23.134
Well, that's--

20:23.178 --> 20:24.571
Uh-huh.

20:24.614 --> 20:27.008
Thank you for coming in
and telling us that.

20:27.051 --> 20:28.966
That's--
that's on the record, so.

20:29.010 --> 20:30.185
We'll let you know

20:30.229 --> 20:32.318
if we have any questions.
- That's fine.

20:32.361 --> 20:33.841
Thank you.

20:33.884 --> 20:36.278
Just doing my part.

20:36.322 --> 20:37.627
I'll walk you out.

20:37.671 --> 20:40.239
Thank you, Detective.
Thank you, Pam.

20:55.079 --> 20:57.995
We're gonna need to rethink.

20:58.039 --> 21:00.520
I agree.

21:00.563 --> 21:03.000
It's about time
we move away from her lies.

21:03.044 --> 21:08.005
She's not lying. She just
keeps changing her story.

21:08.049 --> 21:10.312
And I know Schwartz's
whole case is gonna be

21:10.356 --> 21:12.096
making Pam look guilty,

21:12.140 --> 21:14.490
and with this new muff stuff,

21:14.534 --> 21:17.406
it just could be
distracting in court.

21:17.450 --> 21:19.190
Especially since
she didn't mention

21:19.234 --> 21:20.670
any of it in the first trial.

21:20.714 --> 21:22.977
Well,
she was probably scared.

21:23.020 --> 21:24.195
And then look what happened.

21:24.239 --> 21:26.850
Russ killed Betsy.

21:26.894 --> 21:31.028
We can't too much on Pam
this time around.

21:31.072 --> 21:32.508
We need more hard evidence.

21:32.552 --> 21:35.729
Well, back in 2011,

21:35.772 --> 21:39.298
Pam mentions an email
that Betsy had written her

21:39.341 --> 21:42.475
but not sent.

21:42.518 --> 21:46.348
She said it was a document
on Betsy's computer.

21:46.392 --> 21:48.872
But it details
how she was afraid of Russ,

21:48.916 --> 21:51.353
how he would hold a pillow
over her face,

21:51.397 --> 21:54.138
but no one ever looked for it.

21:54.182 --> 21:55.923
Why?

21:55.966 --> 21:57.881
I don't know.

21:57.925 --> 21:59.579
Well, we need to find
the letter.

21:59.622 --> 22:01.537
Joel, listen to this.

22:01.581 --> 22:04.627
"I woke up to Russ
holding a pillow over my face.

22:04.671 --> 22:05.889
"Didn't know what was going on.

22:05.933 --> 22:07.282
"I broke loose and started
to scream at him,

22:07.326 --> 22:08.631
"asking what he was doing.

22:08.675 --> 22:09.980
"He was said that
he wanted me to know

22:10.024 --> 22:13.854
what dying feels like."

22:13.897 --> 22:15.377
Sounds Huppity.

22:15.421 --> 22:17.379
That was just sent over
from the DA's office.

22:20.426 --> 22:26.606
<i>♪</i>

22:26.649 --> 22:28.172
Remember
the Medical Examiner's report

22:28.216 --> 22:31.350
said that there was bruising
around Betsy's neck?

22:31.393 --> 22:33.221
If Pam wrote this letter
before the murder...

22:33.264 --> 22:34.483
She would be setting up

22:34.527 --> 22:37.007
that Betsy was
gonna be suffocated by Russ.

22:37.051 --> 22:39.096
And that was found
on Betsy's computer,

22:39.140 --> 22:40.402
just like Pam it would.

22:40.446 --> 22:41.403
It's weird
that they sent over

22:41.447 --> 22:43.579
a little piece of paper.

22:43.623 --> 22:44.928
We need the computer.

22:44.972 --> 22:47.931
We need the original
data file analyzed.

22:47.975 --> 22:54.024
<i>♪</i>

22:54.068 --> 22:55.156
Hey, Greg. Joel Schwartz here.

22:55.199 --> 22:56.897
I got a rush job for you.

23:01.554 --> 23:02.772
Front desk says

23:02.816 --> 23:05.645
nobody's changed your diaper
in two days.

23:05.688 --> 23:10.737
I cannot come running every
time you crap yourself, Mom.

23:10.780 --> 23:14.349
Well,
this is what you wanted.

23:14.393 --> 23:17.004
I can't do anything
without you.

23:25.186 --> 23:26.448
Come on.

23:26.492 --> 23:27.797
Mm-hmm.

23:27.841 --> 23:30.321
All right, come on.
- What? No, what?

23:30.365 --> 23:33.107
Damn it!
Where are my glasses?

23:33.150 --> 23:34.456
I know you took 'em.

23:34.500 --> 23:35.805
You take all my things.

23:35.849 --> 23:38.329
I don't know how I raised
such a fat little thief.

23:38.373 --> 23:43.073
I did not take your things.

23:43.117 --> 23:45.511
You should be nicer to me.

23:45.554 --> 23:47.426
Why should I be nice

23:47.469 --> 23:49.819
to a girl
who marries a Gunderson?

23:49.863 --> 23:52.996
I'm married to Mark now, Mom.

23:53.040 --> 23:55.477
Mark. Mark.

23:55.521 --> 23:58.349
Mark, Mark, Mark, Mark.

23:58.393 --> 24:02.223
But you made
a little Gunderson.

24:02.266 --> 24:05.095
And she's still got you beat.

24:05.139 --> 24:09.012
Sarah is a teacher.

24:09.056 --> 24:12.146
And you're what?

24:12.189 --> 24:14.496
On disability or something?

24:14.540 --> 24:16.498
I make a nice living

24:16.542 --> 24:17.978
with my real estate business.

24:18.021 --> 24:21.285
Well, just go flip
your dang houses,

24:21.329 --> 24:23.984
before Sarah takes that too.

24:24.027 --> 24:26.377
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
When a parent hurts a child,</i>

24:26.421 --> 24:28.205
<i>does that hurt get passed on</i>

24:28.249 --> 24:30.643
<i>like a grim inheritance?</i>

24:30.686 --> 24:32.514
All right,
ladies and gentlemen,

24:32.558 --> 24:34.908
the next house
on the auction block:

24:34.951 --> 24:35.865
Derby Street.

24:35.909 --> 24:37.301
It is a beautiful little house

24:37.345 --> 24:39.129
with two bedrooms, a bathroom,

24:39.173 --> 24:40.914
and a wonderful
little kitchenette.

24:43.220 --> 24:45.222
Wonderful opportunity
for a smart buyer.

24:45.266 --> 24:47.660
85, the woman in blue.

24:47.703 --> 24:51.054
Going once, going twice.

24:51.098 --> 24:53.622
95, the woman in pink.

24:53.666 --> 24:56.059
Pam, what are you doing?

24:56.103 --> 24:58.105
I don't think the lender's
gonna give us another loan.

24:58.148 --> 25:00.237
- Shh.
- We shouldn't even be here.

25:00.281 --> 25:02.805
You really gonna let this go?

25:02.849 --> 25:05.242
Do we have enough money?

25:05.286 --> 25:06.766
Bow out, Sarah.

25:06.809 --> 25:09.595
It's only gonna get worse
for ya, trust me.

25:09.638 --> 25:12.685
Okay,
going once, going twice.

25:12.728 --> 25:14.556
Sold to the woman in pink.

25:14.600 --> 25:16.950
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
Pam wins again.</i>

25:16.993 --> 25:18.734
<i>For now.</i>

25:18.778 --> 25:21.302
<i>But could she do it</i> <i>
once more in a court of law?</i>

25:21.345 --> 25:23.130
- Oh, boy.
- Mrs. Hupp.

25:23.173 --> 25:25.132
Why did Betsy
make you the beneficiary?

25:25.175 --> 25:26.612
- Pam.
- Pam!

25:26.655 --> 25:28.439
Any comments?

25:28.483 --> 25:31.094
Mr. Hupp, anything?

25:31.138 --> 25:33.401
Any comment at all?

25:33.444 --> 25:35.142
Anything at all today?

25:35.185 --> 25:38.058
Do you have any comment?

25:39.973 --> 25:41.452
- What's that?
- Someone from the DA's office

25:41.496 --> 25:44.020
sent those over to me anonymously.

25:44.064 --> 25:45.805
And they change everything
for us, Russ.

25:45.848 --> 25:48.459
- What is it?
- Luminol photos.

25:48.503 --> 25:51.245
That's right, perfect pictures.
No camera malfunctions.

25:51.288 --> 25:52.594
And...
- Wait for it.

25:52.638 --> 25:54.857
No signs of blood,
no evidence of a cleanup,

25:54.901 --> 25:57.033
which means the police lied.
- Ha!

26:00.123 --> 26:01.821
<i>♪</i>

26:01.864 --> 26:05.128
Hey.

26:05.172 --> 26:06.826
I can't promise you
we're gonna win.

26:06.869 --> 26:08.001
I think we learned
that last time around.

26:08.044 --> 26:09.916
But I can promise you

26:09.959 --> 26:12.179
that these give us
a much better shot.

26:12.222 --> 26:14.442
I've thought about you
and this case

26:14.485 --> 26:16.096
every damn day
since the last trial,

26:16.139 --> 26:19.055
and I am gonna fight like hell
for you out there, Russ.

26:19.099 --> 26:21.536
I appreciate that.

26:28.151 --> 26:33.330
Mrs. Askey, you may proceed.

26:40.642 --> 26:43.340
"My name is Russell Faria.

26:43.384 --> 26:45.647
"I just got home
from my friend's house,

26:45.691 --> 26:48.258
and my wife killed herself."

26:48.302 --> 26:52.523
That's what the defendant said
on his 911 phone call.

26:52.567 --> 26:54.656
But that was a lie.

26:54.700 --> 26:57.354
The first of many.

26:57.398 --> 27:00.444
Betsy Faria
did not kill herself.

27:00.488 --> 27:02.359
She was murdered.

27:02.403 --> 27:05.667
And the state will show
that the only person

27:05.711 --> 27:10.454
with the means, motive,
and opportunity

27:10.498 --> 27:13.066
was Russell Faria.

27:13.109 --> 27:16.547
<i>♪</i>

27:16.591 --> 27:18.854
Judge, our case
will be based on evidence,

27:18.898 --> 27:20.203
not theories.

27:20.247 --> 27:22.205
And the evidence
will clearly show

27:22.249 --> 27:24.599
that Russell Faria
did not murder his wife.

27:24.643 --> 27:26.427
The person who murdered
Betsy Faria

27:26.470 --> 27:28.690
was the last person
to see her alive,

27:28.734 --> 27:31.780
was the person who got
the insurance payout,

27:31.824 --> 27:33.782
<i>and the person</i> <i>
who has consistently lied</i>

27:33.826 --> 27:36.611
<i>about every single detail</i> <i>
of this case.</i>

27:39.614 --> 27:46.577
<i>♪</i>

27:51.844 --> 27:53.759
Detective McCarrick?

27:53.802 --> 27:57.371
<i>♪</i>

27:57.414 --> 27:58.720
<i>Detective McCarrick,</i>

27:58.764 --> 28:01.114
nobody followed up
with Pam Hupp's husband

28:01.157 --> 28:03.725
to do an actual interview
with him alone.

28:03.769 --> 28:04.900
No.

28:04.944 --> 28:06.423
Nobody bothered
to seize his phone,

28:06.467 --> 28:08.730
to verify when
Pam's message was left?

28:08.774 --> 28:11.428
- No.
- Hmm.

28:11.472 --> 28:14.388
And nobody--nobody bothered
to check with the neighbors

28:14.431 --> 28:16.651
to see
when she might have got home.

28:16.695 --> 28:19.088
Not to my knowledge.

28:19.132 --> 28:21.221
Can anyone testify
where Pam Hupp was

28:21.264 --> 28:23.832
at the time of the murder?

28:23.876 --> 28:26.182
No.

28:26.226 --> 28:28.532
Were you aware that
Pam Hupp's financial situation

28:28.576 --> 28:30.317
was so dire
at the time of Betsy's murder

28:30.360 --> 28:32.275
that she was
several months behind

28:32.319 --> 28:36.062
on her COBRA payments
for her health insurance?

28:36.105 --> 28:37.063
I was not.

28:37.106 --> 28:41.067
<i>♪</i>

28:41.110 --> 28:43.634
How much did Pam gain
when Betsy died?

28:43.678 --> 28:49.031
<i>♪</i>

28:49.075 --> 28:53.949
$150,000.

28:53.993 --> 28:56.517
No further questions.

28:56.560 --> 29:03.480
<i>♪</i>

29:10.009 --> 29:11.532
Daniel Williams.

29:11.575 --> 29:17.190
<i>♪</i>

29:17.233 --> 29:19.366
"I need to change
my life insurance policy

29:19.409 --> 29:21.585
"out of his name,
but can't let him know

29:21.629 --> 29:24.588
"that I have taken him off
as beneficiary.

29:24.632 --> 29:26.112
"I need your help.

29:26.155 --> 29:28.288
"I am so tired from the cancer.

29:28.331 --> 29:32.988
"I am so afraid of staying out
in Troy alone with Russ.

29:33.032 --> 29:34.337
"If something happens to me,

29:34.381 --> 29:36.905
would you please show this
to the police?"

29:36.949 --> 29:38.994
And that was addressed
to Pam Hupp.

29:39.038 --> 29:40.387
Correct.

29:40.430 --> 29:43.433
And as a member of
the Cybercrimes Task Force,

29:43.477 --> 29:48.482
it's your job to examine
all the digital evidence.

29:48.525 --> 29:52.660
Can you please tell the court
where you found this document?

29:52.703 --> 29:54.880
I found the pdoc
on Betsy Faria's computer,

29:54.923 --> 29:57.230
State's Exhibit 3.

29:57.273 --> 29:59.972
No future questions.

30:00.015 --> 30:05.934
<i>♪</i>

30:05.978 --> 30:07.849
What's this letter?

30:07.893 --> 30:09.329
Don't worry about it.

30:09.372 --> 30:13.115
The defense would like to call
Detective Michael Merkel.

30:13.159 --> 30:14.595
After you took
the Luminol photos,

30:14.638 --> 30:16.205
you testified,
back in the first trial,

30:16.249 --> 30:19.600
that they showed
absolutely nothing,

30:19.643 --> 30:22.908
because of a malfunction
in the camera

30:22.951 --> 30:24.170
that has since been repaired.

30:24.213 --> 30:25.954
Is that correct?

30:25.998 --> 30:29.044
So there were no photographs
that were developed that day.

30:29.088 --> 30:31.264
I don't believe so.
No, sir.

30:31.307 --> 30:36.660
<i>♪</i>

30:36.704 --> 30:39.402
I'd like to show you
what is marked as

30:39.446 --> 30:41.274
Defendant's Exhibit O.

30:41.317 --> 30:43.885
What you see?

30:43.929 --> 30:45.539
It would be

30:45.582 --> 30:48.237
the Luminol photos
from the scene.

30:48.281 --> 30:50.152
Where did he get those?

30:50.196 --> 30:52.633
And do they show
absolutely nothing?

30:52.676 --> 30:54.330
No, sir.

30:54.374 --> 30:56.593
There's 130 of them there.

30:56.637 --> 31:02.817
Pull one out. Any one.
At random.

31:02.861 --> 31:04.253
What is that a picture of?

31:04.297 --> 31:05.733
Looks like a sink drain.

31:05.776 --> 31:08.692
- Is that absolutely nothing?
- No.

31:08.736 --> 31:11.304
Pull out another one.
Any one.

31:11.347 --> 31:13.262
<i>♪</i>

31:13.306 --> 31:15.351
Now what's that?
- Floor tile.

31:15.395 --> 31:17.614
- Is that absolutely nothing?
- No, sir.

31:17.658 --> 31:19.268
So when you said
that the photographs

31:19.312 --> 31:20.791
contained absolutely nothing,

31:20.835 --> 31:23.272
you actually meant
nothing you wanted to see.

31:23.316 --> 31:24.926
- Objection.
- Sustained.

31:24.970 --> 31:27.320
You testified in 2013
that those photographs

31:27.363 --> 31:28.495
contained absolutely nothing,

31:28.538 --> 31:31.715
but today,
you now see 130 photographs

31:31.759 --> 31:34.109
of absolutely something,
is that correct?

31:34.153 --> 31:36.720
- Yes, that's correct.
- Yes, so there's no evidence

31:36.764 --> 31:40.289
that Russ cleaned up any blood
in those photos, is there?

31:40.333 --> 31:41.812
- No.
- Thank you.

31:41.856 --> 31:43.292
No further questions.

31:43.336 --> 31:50.038
<i>♪</i>

31:50.082 --> 31:53.128
The defense calls Greg Chatton.

31:53.172 --> 31:55.739
I work in digital forensics
for law enforcement matters.

31:55.783 --> 31:57.567
And you examined
the computer file

31:57.611 --> 31:59.961
the prosecution claims
is a letter from Betsy Faria?

32:00.005 --> 32:01.745
Yes, I validated the file

32:01.789 --> 32:04.400
and documented the date
and times the file was created.

32:04.444 --> 32:06.141
Can you explain to the court
what you found?

32:06.185 --> 32:08.796
Mrs. Faria
was running Windows 2003,

32:08.839 --> 32:11.016
and when a document is created,
she would be tagged

32:11.059 --> 32:13.496
within the metadata
of the file automatically.

32:13.540 --> 32:17.152
This is something
that the user cannot control.

32:17.196 --> 32:19.285
That's a lot.

32:19.328 --> 32:21.940
So who did the metadata say

32:21.983 --> 32:24.290
created the alleged letter?

32:24.333 --> 32:28.729
- It said "unknown."
- "Unknown"?

32:28.772 --> 32:30.992
Hmm.
I wonder how that happened.

32:31.036 --> 32:32.515
There are only two ways:

32:32.559 --> 32:34.691
someone changed the author
to "unknown,"

32:34.735 --> 32:36.693
or the file was created
on another computer

32:36.737 --> 32:38.565
and then copied over.
- I see.

32:38.608 --> 32:40.175
You found something else
interesting in the metadata.

32:40.219 --> 32:41.524
What was that?

32:41.568 --> 32:43.178
The metadata tagged
this document

32:43.222 --> 32:45.702
as being created in Word '97.

32:45.746 --> 32:47.922
Was Word '97 installed
on Betsy's computer?

32:47.966 --> 32:49.184
No.

32:49.228 --> 32:50.533
So it would be impossible

32:50.577 --> 32:52.057
for that document
to have been created

32:52.100 --> 32:54.363
on Betsy's computer.
- Yes.

32:54.407 --> 32:55.669
Which means
it had to have been

32:55.712 --> 32:57.323
copied over
from a different computer.

32:57.366 --> 32:58.585
That's correct.

32:58.628 --> 33:02.458
No further questions.

33:04.286 --> 33:07.028
The witness may step down.

33:07.072 --> 33:10.379
Are there any more witnesses
for the state?

33:13.426 --> 33:20.737
<i>♪</i>

33:21.129 --> 33:23.044
Leah.

33:23.088 --> 33:25.003
Are you going to call Pam?

33:28.049 --> 33:34.751
<i>♪</i>

33:34.795 --> 33:37.232
The state rests, Your Honor.

33:37.276 --> 33:38.668
Why didn't they call Pam?

33:38.712 --> 33:40.235
If there's something
more damaging,

33:40.279 --> 33:42.498
we could discover it on cross.

33:42.542 --> 33:44.152
We could finally nail her.

33:44.196 --> 33:45.849
Very well.

33:45.893 --> 33:47.851
Are there any more witnesses
for the defense?

33:47.895 --> 33:54.815
<i>♪</i>

34:02.475 --> 34:03.954
The defense rests,
Your Honor.

34:03.998 --> 34:10.526
<i>♪</i>

34:10.570 --> 34:13.964
We don't need her lies
in this court.

34:14.008 --> 34:17.011
<i>♪</i>

34:19.274 --> 34:20.449
Please rise.

34:23.452 --> 34:30.416
<i>♪</i>

34:35.464 --> 34:41.122
There's no question
this was a brutal murder.

34:41.166 --> 34:43.081
And I'm sorry for the family

34:43.124 --> 34:47.737
who had to experience
such a horror.

34:47.781 --> 34:51.785
But the investigation
of this case by law enforcement

34:51.828 --> 34:53.308
is rather disturbing,

34:53.352 --> 34:54.831
and frankly,

34:54.875 --> 34:57.921
raised more questions
than answers.

34:57.965 --> 35:01.142
<i>♪</i>

35:01.186 --> 35:04.145
Consequently, as to count one,

35:04.189 --> 35:06.191
murder in the first degree,

35:06.234 --> 35:07.888
court finds the defendant,

35:07.931 --> 35:10.586
Russell Scott Faria,

35:10.630 --> 35:11.935
not guilty.

35:11.979 --> 35:14.155
Oh!

35:14.199 --> 35:18.290
As to count two,
armed criminal action,

35:18.333 --> 35:21.858
the court finds the defendant,
Russell Scott Faria,

35:21.902 --> 35:24.600
not guilty.

35:27.647 --> 35:34.523
<i>♪</i>

36:12.692 --> 36:19.873
<i>♪</i>

36:27.446 --> 36:32.451
So Mom's killer just gets
to walk away and that's it?

36:32.494 --> 36:35.541
<i>♪</i>

36:35.584 --> 36:36.977
Looks like it.

36:37.020 --> 36:40.894
<i>♪</i>

36:45.072 --> 36:50.686
<i>♪</i>

36:50.730 --> 36:53.123
Leah blew it.

36:53.167 --> 36:56.475
All she had to do
was call me to the stand.

36:56.518 --> 36:58.216
Here she comes.

37:02.045 --> 37:06.398
<i>♪</i>

37:09.792 --> 37:13.753
Joel Schwartz is here.

37:13.796 --> 37:17.452
Thank you, Tina.

37:17.496 --> 37:18.801
How you doing, Leah?

37:18.845 --> 37:20.281
Just great, Joel.

37:20.325 --> 37:21.891
Look, I'm not sure
you're gonna want to do this,

37:21.935 --> 37:23.241
but we have a lot of research

37:23.284 --> 37:24.633
that we are willing to share,

37:24.677 --> 37:28.898
if you decide
to reopen the Faria case.

37:28.942 --> 37:30.596
We had the right guy,
but thanks.

37:33.076 --> 37:34.252
All right.
Well, if you change your mind.

37:34.295 --> 37:36.036
Yeah,
you'll be my first call.

37:39.039 --> 37:46.133
<i>♪</i>

37:46.176 --> 37:48.483
- Can I ask you a question?
- Of course.

37:48.527 --> 37:50.050
How do you like
working for her?

37:50.093 --> 37:53.271
<i>♪</i>

37:53.314 --> 37:54.533
I don't work for Leah.

37:54.576 --> 37:55.708
I work for the county.

37:55.751 --> 37:58.188
Doesn't matter
whose name's on the door.

37:58.232 --> 38:01.104
This town
is lucky to have you.

38:01.148 --> 38:08.286
<i>♪</i>

38:15.684 --> 38:17.207
Hi, this is DA Askey.

38:17.251 --> 38:19.297
I'd like the Sheriff's Office
to draw up

38:19.340 --> 38:22.648
a destruction
of evidence order.

38:22.691 --> 38:25.999
Yes, all evidence
related to the Faria case.

38:26.042 --> 38:31.004
That's items 1 through 214.

38:31.047 --> 38:32.614
Yep, and the evidence logs.

38:32.658 --> 38:34.181
Thank you.

38:34.224 --> 38:35.313
<i>I still think</i> <i>
there's evidence out there</i>

38:35.356 --> 38:36.705
<i>I never received.</i>

38:36.749 --> 38:39.012
When I finally got
the cell tower triangulation,

38:39.055 --> 38:40.796
it showed that Pam
had not gotten more than,

38:40.840 --> 38:41.971
at the very most,

38:42.015 --> 38:43.799
about three miles
from the house.

38:43.843 --> 38:45.975
And at the very least,
she was still at the house.

38:46.019 --> 38:47.977
<i>And the fact that she lied</i> <i>
about where she was</i>

38:48.021 --> 38:49.805
<i>when she called the victim--</i>

38:49.849 --> 38:51.807
<i>but I couldn't get into any</i> <i>
of that when she testified--</i>

38:51.851 --> 38:56.159
<i>well, the 25 years</i> <i>
I've been practicing law,</i>

38:56.203 --> 38:58.161
<i>I have never seen</i> <i>
anything like it.</i>

38:59.989 --> 39:01.861
<i>narrator: In everyday life,</i> <i>
we're all the heroes</i>

39:01.904 --> 39:04.385
<i>of our own stories.</i>

39:04.429 --> 39:08.041
<i>But what happens</i> <i>
when our story gets told?</i>

39:08.084 --> 39:13.002
Can you believe this crap?

39:13.046 --> 39:16.702
Maybe nobody will see it.

39:16.745 --> 39:18.268
<i>narrator:</i> <i>
For the first time,</i>

39:18.312 --> 39:24.623
<i>Pam wasn't in control</i> <i>
over her own story.</i>

39:24.666 --> 39:27.190
Hello, missy?

39:27.234 --> 39:28.322
- No.
- Hello--

39:28.366 --> 39:29.976
No, no, no.
No, no, no, no, no.

39:30.019 --> 39:33.109
I'm cutting you off.

39:33.153 --> 39:35.024
12 bucks a pop.

39:35.068 --> 39:36.374
12.

39:36.417 --> 39:39.115
What, now you can't
buy me a drink because

39:39.159 --> 39:41.117
you bought Sarah's house
out from under her?

39:41.161 --> 39:43.076
It wasn't hers.

39:43.119 --> 39:45.470
You owe her big time.

39:45.513 --> 39:48.037
I have half a mind
to cut you out of the will

39:48.081 --> 39:50.213
and stick her in your slot.

39:50.257 --> 39:51.954
I pay for Autumndale.

39:51.998 --> 39:55.393
I hate Autumndale.

39:55.436 --> 39:59.440
It smells like spiderwebs
and soup.

39:59.484 --> 40:02.312
You know, you're done, Pam.

40:02.356 --> 40:04.184
I'm cutting you off.

40:09.319 --> 40:16.414
<i>♪</i>

40:43.136 --> 40:47.619
Aww, thanks, hon.

40:51.536 --> 40:53.581
You really do take care of me.

40:53.625 --> 40:58.194
I don't know
what I'd do with ya.

40:58.238 --> 41:05.332
<i>♪</i>

41:17.039 --> 41:22.392
<i>♪</i>

41:22.436 --> 41:24.786
She is down for the count
up there.

41:24.830 --> 41:28.050
Won't be down for dinner.

41:28.094 --> 41:30.139
Or breakfast.
- Breakfast, too?

41:30.183 --> 41:32.228
Yeah, she needs her rest.

41:32.272 --> 41:33.491
If you don't from her,

41:33.534 --> 41:36.145
maybe pop in around lunchtime.

41:36.189 --> 41:38.800
Sure thing, Miss Pam.

41:38.844 --> 41:40.802
Happy Halloween.

41:40.846 --> 41:42.717
<i>♪</i>

41:42.761 --> 41:46.199
Trick or treat.

41:46.242 --> 41:49.811
- I like your costume!
- Ah!

41:49.855 --> 41:52.379
Will you please wait for me?

42:02.781 --> 42:05.305
Whoa.

42:05.348 --> 42:07.829
That almost looks real.

42:10.876 --> 42:13.182
<i>♪</i>

42:19.232 --> 42:25.325
<i>♪</i>

